qas.question: Who was discontinued in the Commonwealth realms?

answers.text: Appointments to the Order of the British Empire

qas.question: Who established a national system of honours and awards?

answers.text: Order of Australia, the Order of Canada, and the New Zealand Order of Merit

qas.question: How were the different levels of award and honour reflected the imperial system?

context: <a0_0>Appointments to the Order of the British Empire<a0_0/> were discontinued in those Commonwealth realms that established a national system of honours and awards such as the <a1_0>Order of Australia, the Order of Canada, and the New Zealand Order of Merit<a1_0/>. In many of these systems, the different levels of award and honour reflect the Imperial system they replaced. <a2_0>Canada, Australia, and New Zealand<a2_0/> all have (in increasing level of precedence) Members of, Officers of, and Companions to (rather than Commanders of) their respective orders, with both Australia and New Zealand having <a3_0>Knights and Dames<a3_0/> as their highest classes.
